  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial Celebrating the Pacification of the Northern Territories
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your sage wisdom penetrates all things, and your strategy ensures victory without fail.
    The barbarian tribes come to submit; no second campaign is needed.
    Wherever news of triumph reaches, joy rises like morning mist.

    I humbly revere Your Majesty—holy and divine, cultured and martial alike.
    You inherit the mandate of the Two Emperors and Three Kings,
    Establishing the Great Ultimate and unifying all lands beneath heaven as one household.

    Yet those barbarous whelps, gasping for breath in their barren wastelands,
    Still dare to wield their venomous fangs?
    The praying mantis scarcely dares raise its arm against the heavens.
    Where the celestial spear falls, the savage hordes surrender at once.
    From all directions come tributes of praise; eternity holds your renown.

    I confess my unworthiness—a man of modest talents
    Temporarily governing a humble province,
    Unfit to join the grand procession of congratulations.
    Yet from afar I offer this humble verse, prostrating before the Son of Heaven.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Two Emperors and Three Kings' refer to the legendary sage rulers of ancient China, representing the ideal of virtuous governance.
    - The 'celestial spear' is a metaphor for imperial military power and divine mandate.
    - The reference to the 'praying mantis raising its arm' alludes to a famous Daoist parable about the futility of resistance against overwhelming force.
